06573nam a22009735i 9783110533651DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105336517 a10.1515/97831105336512doi  a(DE-B1597)477260  a(OCoLC)1046612495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aKNQ120b.V538 2018 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a349.5109/04522300aVictims, Perpetrators, and the Role of Law in Maoist China :bA Case-Study Approach /ced. by Puck Engman, Daniel Leese. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 205 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformations of Modern China ,x2511-6029 ;v100tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Beyond “Destruction” and “Lawlessness”: The Legal System during the Cultural Revolution -- t2. The Intelligence Sleeper Who Never Was: Han Fuying and Case 5004 -- t3. A Different Category of Life: The Counterrevolutionary Case of a Rural Schoolteacher -- t4. Vetting the People’s Servant: On the Principles of Revolutionary Integrity -- t5. A Policeman, His Gun, and an Alleged Rape: Competing Appeals for Justice in Tianjin, 1966–1979 -- t6. From Denial to Apology: Narrative Strategies of a “Perpetrator” after the Cultural Revolution -- t7. The Floating Fate of a Rebel Leader in Guangxi, 1966–1984 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEine erstmalige Analyse maoistischer Justiz auf Basis von Originalfallakten, die aufgrund ihrer plastischen Details einen tiefen Einblick in die chinesische Rechts-, Politik- und Sozialgeschichte geben. Durch die Betonung der Akteuersebene wird, jenseits von Metadiskursen, der totalitäre Charakter der frühen Volksrepublik China und der mehr oder minder großer Spielraum von Angeklagten, Richtern und politischer Führung ausgelotet. Der Band versammelt chinesische, europäische und amerikanische Wissenschaftler, um gemeinsam eine Revision des bisherigen Forschungsstandes zu ermöglichen.  aThe relationship between politics and law in the early People’sRepublic of China was highly contentious. Periods of intentionallyexcessive campaign justice intersected with attempts to carve outprofessional standards of adjudication and to offer retroactive justicefor those deemed to have been unjustly persecuted. How were victims andperpetrators defined and dealt with during different stages of theMaoist era and beyond? How was law practiced, understood, and contestedin local contexts? This volume adopts a case study approach to shedlight on these complex questions. By way of a close reading of originalcase files from the grassroots level, the contributors detailprocedures and question long-held assumptions, not least about theCultural Revolution as a period of “lawlessness.”  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLawzChinaxHistoryvCases. 0aLawzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngman, Puck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngman, Puck, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuoqing, Song, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaiguang, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeese, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeese, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLizhi, Xu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMan, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoenhals